Section 4: 

This law explains when and how any company or individual can use your personal data (such as your name or phone number).
​
Any individual or company can use your data only under two conditions:
1. ​With your consent: When you have voluntarily given them permission to use your data.
2  ​For legitimate uses: Certain essential government or legal functions where data can be used even without your permission (such as during emergencies or for government schemes).

Apart from this, the use of data must always be for a "Lawful Purpose". Lawful purpose simply means—any activity that is not expressly forbidden by the law of the country.

Example of Consent (Point A): Suppose Lakshit downloads a new shopping app. When starting the app, he is asked for his phone number and address and there is a box at the bottom that reads, "I agree to share my information." When Lakshit ticks that box, he is giving his consent to the company to use his data. This is completely valid and legal.
​Example of Unlawful Purpose: On the other hand, if a company takes Lakshit's phone number to threaten him or commit fraud, it will be considered an "unlawful purpose." By law, data cannot be used for any such activities.
